    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Movie Violence: Too Much Ado?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Rebecca Schlam Lutto letter scores impact of violent films and games on young people</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Hollywood Insiders Give Thumbs-Down to Critics'' (news article, Sept. 18):</p>
        <p>You quote the filmmaker John Waters as saying: ''You show me a kid who's not sneaking into R-rated movies, and I'll show you a failure in the making. The future C.E.O.'s of America are all sneaking into R-rated movies.'' This speaks to me directly.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Hollywood Insiders Give Thumbs-Down to Critics'' (news article, Sept. 18):</p>
        <p>You quote the filmmaker John Waters as saying: ''You show me a kid who's not sneaking into R-rated movies, and I'll show you a failure in the making. The future C.E.O.'s of America are all sneaking into R-rated movies.'' This speaks to me directly.</p>
        <p>As a parent who is a shellshocked veteran of America's culture wars, I would like to ask the Hollywood moguls a question: Without the aggression taught by violent films and games, might not that child otherwise be a future teacher, healer or environmentalist?</p>
        <p>REBECCA SCHLAM LUTTO  West Palm Beach, Fla., Sept. 18, 2000</p>
      </block>
